The AMAZON_SALES table is created using data ingested from the Amazon Sales report from the Amazon Developer Console. Note: this data contains granular transaction level information relevant for sales analysis and forecasting (i.e., charge vs refund events,  earnings amount) with detail by Amazon marketplace (ex: Amazon.jp, Amazon.ca, Amazon.es) and SKU (ex: com.disney.monthly.disneyplus7dft.amazon, com.disney.yearly.disneyplus7dft.amazon). This report is ingested on a daily basis and 1) updates data for the current month report (new days are appended throughout the month) and 2) updates data for all historical months. All previous months are processed because Amazon can potentially change data for previous month reports. Therefore, all previous months are ingested again during each monthly ingestion event to ensure all data is up to date.

The APP_PERFORMANCE_LIFECYCLE_EVENTS is aggregation of lifecycle events for application performance. They intended to capture the start and end of app activities and can be used to answer questions like: How much time do users spend waiting for images to load, how frequently do users see placeholder images, and from app icon launch, how long does it take before the user can take action? Currently lifecycle events aim to capture the time it takes for blocking and critical network calls to run during app launch sequences. Blocking calls prevent necessary search/image calls from starting. Critical calls provide data necessary to draw UI. Those calls are, but not limited to, dictionary lookups, config lookups, requests to accounts, gobal calls for session / token generation, BAM-sdk configurations, and requests for images like logo.

Ingests processed and transformed S3 access logs as part of Consumption Analytics workflow. This table is updated daily and calculates the lookback % concentration by joining to the minimum partition date table. This table serves as a precursor aggregate for informing downstream ream gold tables and Looker dashboards.

The CONTENT_METADATA table contains DmcVideo and Airing data for Disney+, ESPN+ and Star+ ingested by the Experience Services team. Because the metadata records capture data which may be better represented as top-level fields in the table, a number of tags are lifted out of the metadata arrays and surfaced as their own columns.

The CONTENT_EVENT_METADATA_LANGUAGE_R table contains Stitch data for Airing and Video, as ingested by the Experience Services team. This data comes from a new event field, Sports Event which is hydrated on to existing data that comes from DMC.  The metadata_ids here are same and should be joinable to data (Airing and Video) in CONTENT_METADATA assets. Because the metadata captured in this new event data may be better represented as top-level fields in the table, a number of tags are lifted out of the metadata arrays and surfaced as their own columns.  The grain of the table is at metadata_id and language_iso_code. The follow sub-entities have been lifted up and flattened and select fields for each is added as a new column. Note that these entities are lifted up and flattened per metadata_id and language_iso_code based on each language entry found in that entity. Venue League Sport Competitors

The CONTENT_HYDRATED_METADATA_D table contains Stitch data for Airing and Video, as ingested by the Experience Services team. This data comes from a new event field, Sports Event which is hydrated on to existing data that comes from DMC. In this table the new hydrated event object is added as whole as one giant json blob. The metadata_ids here are same and should be joinable to data (Airing and Video) in CONTENT_METADATA assets. The grain of the table is at metadata_id.

The WATCH_WATCHES table is the aggregation of completed watch events published by the Watch Generator. A watch is defined as a viewer watching a single piece of media for a given time. The start time and end time are interpolated based on the following heuristics: A watch starts the first time an event is received for a user and media which is not already part of an existing watch A watch ends when no new events for a particular user and media have been received for a pre-defined period of time, currently one hour Using these two heuristics, the Media Consumption Reporting app aggregates telemetry and viewing activity data into watches.

The Watch watches table will be enriched by joining to session_d, device_session_d and account_session_d. -session_d: When a device visits the edge, a session is created and expires after 4 hours.  Attributes are associated with the session from Account, Device, Profile, Subscriptions, and more.  The subscription array is exploded and entitlements and other attributes are made available as arrays. account_session_d: IPSE account data is joined to session on an hourly basis, and account attributes including test flags are included -device_session_d:  IPSE device data is joined to session on an hourly basis, and account attributes including test flags are included Each hour watch data is enriched with session data. One hour of watch data is joined to the last 10 hours of session data.  Sessions last for 4 hours (so we included 5 hours for that), and watches should mostly be complete in 5 hours.

WATCH_ORIGIN_D provides visibility into the origin of a watch event. The origin is the page / button that was clicked on in order to start watching a particular piece of media, and is encapsulated in the related GLIMPSEV2_INTERACTION_EVENTS. WATCH_ORIGIN_D is the set of Glimpse interaction events that can be joined to a particular WATCH_WATCHES / WATCH_F hourly partition.
